Herodotus speaks of several rivers (the scamander in Asia, ,and others in Thrace, Thessaly, and Achaia) being dried up by the enormous host of Xerxes drinking of them. This is easily explained. These rivers are not perennial streams full of water. The army could find water-heles only in many of them, and these they may have exhausted. Sostratus seems to have been a poet who wrote of the exploits of Xerxes. ‘Madidis alis ’ is supposed to mean that he got heated with the exertion of reciting his poetry.
